Do you want the same meat freezer set up I have? 

I have the absolute best sources of beef in central Texas. I have visited and vetted tons of ranches, know which ones have the best regenerative practices with the healthiest animals, know how to work with processors and butchers to get the best cuts and best tasting meat, and get it all for the cheapest price. 

I’m now trying to link up farmers and people in the area to make it dead simple to buy beef in bulk. You text me, I go set up a freezer at your house, stock it full of beef, and even set up a smartphone temperature alarm so you don’t lose 200lbs of meat like I did this year.

Only taking a few spots right now to see how this goes. 

I’m personally making no money on this, I just want to enable you to have the best food possible and support the ranchers and farmers we all truly depend on. 

DM me if interested!

The highlight of 2022 was hands down marrying @marthaheymans on our farm in November.🤵🏻‍♂️👰🏻‍♀️

What I thought was going to be just an expensive party turned out to be the most impactful and incredible day of my life. 

Martha has a sneaky way of surprising me with her thoughtfulness and intention and absolutely blew me away with how all her hard work paid off creating the most unique, beautiful, and meaningful event possible. I’m a lucky man! 

Getting married and doing it your own way is extremely underrated. 10/10. Highly recommend. 

Hard to top, but excited for what’s to come in 2023! 🥂

📸 by the amazing @sarakbyrne

Sometimes you have to make your own decision instead of deferring the to "authorities."

What are you not waiting on the experts to tell you to do/not do?

Hey meat lovers, it's me again! 

Last month I announced a program of getting tons of people loaded up on the best possible local beef from regenerative ranches in central Texas. We filled a bunch of freezers and bellies and now we're upgrading our offering. 

By popular demand, we are now doing 10lb and 20lb mixed meat box subscriptions! You can choose between: 
🥩 Beef only
🥩 Beef + 🐓 Chicken
🥩 Beef + 🐓 Chicken + 🐷 Pork

This is by far the best meat you can get. 100% grass-fed grass-finished beef & moved daily. Our pigs and chickens are 100% corn & soy free, & always on pasture.

Head over to rootedlocalmeats.com to get your box today. 

Every subscription means more stability for the actual producer. They helps us predict supply needed and effectively guarantee demand for the farmers so they can properly manage their herds.

Companies like ButcherBox source from massive industrial low quality farms from Australia and Brazil, feed their animals tons of corn and soy, and you can see it and taste it.

Their meat is literally pale, gray, lifeless, and tastes like cardboard.

And our boxes are CHEAPER than theirs. You guys, this is a literal no brainer. 

If you want to help change the food system and keep small local farms alive, please go over and get your box at rootedlocalmeats.com 

And no -- we are NOT shipping our meat in the mail. Sorry! The entire point of this project is to support local farms and get you the healthiest and best tasting meat.

Plus, it's the right thing to do. How can meat be "regenerative" if you are shipping frozen packages all around the world?

If you're not in Austin, TX, tag someone you know who is, drop your area in the comments and hopefully we will be there soon!
And then there was light...

There's a lot of talk lately about how obesity is now considered simply a genetic disease. 

How could this be the case when not even 100 years ago obesity was rare? 

Follow the money. If we classify obesity as something you have no control over, a genetic curse, pharmaceutical companies can now prescribe medications that can free you from the prison cell of your genetics. One simple pill and you'll cure your genetic disease!

The problem is obesity isn't a genetic disease.

Obesity is a symptom of broken metabolism and improper fuel sources driven by an environment that is not fit for our human bodies. 

We live in an environment full of ultra-processed food-like substances, pesticides, herbicides, air full of pollutants, water full of contaminants, disconnection from nature and  anything else that lives, lack of sunlight, extreme amount of chronic stress, no purpose, no meaning, no security, unresolved trauma, and little meaningful human connection. 

Put a rat in a cage in a lab by itself and feed it soybean oil and sugar under massive amounts of stress and artificial light and it will also get obese.

The genetics didn't change, the environment did. 

Don't fall for all of this nonsense. Fix your environment, fix your health.

🤯 Same batch of pigs. The top are from our corn-free, soy-free batch, and the bottom from corn and soy batch. 

Same litter, same land, same conditions. 

Sent off for nutrition analysis. Very curious on how the results are going to come back!

Did you know that when you eat seed oils, and 99% of pork and chicken that are fed corn and soy, the fatty acids embed into your body for over TWO YEARS. 🤯

You are literally what you eat.

Why are processed foods so bad for you? 

It’s not the “processing” itself. We’ve been processing foods for thousands of years. But we were processing them to improve nutrition and digestibility. 

Now we’re processing foods to increase profits. 

When food process them to increase profits, we end up with a fat, sick, and suffering population. 
@tyrbeal talks about why this is.

Follow the money. Stop buying from Big Food. Support your local farmers and ranchers. Get healthy.

“Eat less, move more!” 🚩🚩🚩

We’ve been told this is how we fix our obesity crisis. It’s absurd. 

Our food environment has billions upon billions of dollars of investment to make the most addicting foods that literally wire your brain to consume more. You’re not going to win that battle. 

Ditch the processed trash. Don’t let Big Food make money off of you. Eat real food. 

@tyrbeal

Carnivores will tell you plants will kill you. 
Vegans will tell you meat will kill you. 

But what’s actually killing people? Ultra-processed foods full of seed oils, refined flours, and refined sugars, designed to addict you so Big Food can make money off of you getting fat, sick, and depressed.

Don’t buy the food camp hype. Eat food that spoils that makes you feel good.

📈📈📈 Graphs of the correlation between the amount of glyphosate in our food system and rates of autism, dementia, diabetes, and Celiac disease. 

These may be spurious correlations, or they may not be. 

One thing is clear: something in our environment is poisoning us.

What do you think?

The sun is not our enemy. ☀️

If you spend 95% of your time indoors, work on graded exposure so your skin can adapt. 

Enjoy your summer without fear.

How has todays propaganda on plant-based foods changed your mind when it comes to eating meat?

@dranthonygustin states that based on the data,  people are eating less and less red meat and they’re eating more and more pork and chicken. 

Why should you question this push to eat less red meat?

Well, nutritionally red meat is not only more nutrient dense than pork and chicken, but “we can indefinitely grow these animals and raise them and eat them and participate in this ecosystem.

There is effectively zero sustainable way to have pork and chicken. “

Do you agree with this data?

Hi! I have been quiet on here lately as I've been doing a ton of research and experimenting.

As soon as I thought I had it all figured out I realized how wrong I was about so many things. 

I have been diving down the rabbit hole on redox, "quantum biology," circadian biology, and all things grounding and light and my mind keeps getting blown at how much I am learning that I missed before. 

The adjustments to my day have been minor (and FREE), but the payoff has been huge. I have more energy than I have had in 5 years.

Grateful to the many people who are speaking about these topics who I've learned so much from like @georgiesgardens @sarahkleinerwellness and @drjackkruse 

Just released a podcast with @georgiesgardens and one with @sarahkleinerwellness coming soon. 

Feel free to ask any questions you have. I'll be happy to continue to talk about this as I learn more. The rabbit hole continues... 🐰

Why do you think our health is collapsing as a societu!?

My take: Rapidly changing our environment. We've created a human zoo in almost every way possible and it is destroying us.

Food, movement, stress, sleep, sunlight, water, purpose/work, and relationships are all completely unrecognizable and on top of that were being constantly bathed in a toxic soup of chemicals.

The bad news? No one is coming to open your zoo cage for you. Your tissues have atrophied and your wild instinct is muted. 

The good news? You can open it yourself. Once you start restoring your natural environment you'll never go back.

I used to think yolk color meant something. 

Then I learned about chicken feed and how everyone manipulates their feed to get orange yolks. 

REMINDER: “pasture-raised” doesn’t mean “feed free.”

Pasture raised birds still get tons of feed. You want to know their conditions, how much pasture they get, how fresh that pasture is, how many birds per foot, what is in that supplemental feed etc. 

Best way to know is to go. You’ll know immediately if you want to feed your family food from the farm based on your brilliant human intuition. Trust it.

Letting our primal instincts tell us what to do in our modern environments is typically a recipe for disaster.

"Eat whatever you want!" doesn't work when you have access to a modern grocery store, but it does work when you have the constraints of eating local, seasonal foods. 

I'm starting to believe "Sleep as much as you want!" is the same thing. 

Our modern sleep environments are ultra comfortable, quiet, and dark. The way we would have slept for 99.99% of our human history involved uncomfortable surfaces, massive temp swings, animal noises, sunlight, many other people, etc. 

For the last year or so, I've been sleeping as much as my body wants. Total sleep amount has been creeping up over that time, lately averaging 9 hours a night. I've also been increasingly groggy after I wake up. 

I'm not going to go sleep outside, so I started using alarms to force my body out of sleep, much like the external environment would have in the past.

I recently started switching to getting up to alarms. I'm now getting 7-7.5 hrs of sleep a night and I feel WAY better throughout the day with alertness, need for naps, energy levels, etc.

It started by feeling very tired, but only for the first 15-20 minutes of waking up. Just like when you start eating real food, it's not as tasty as Butterfingers and Oreos. Then you realize how much better you feel throughout the day. 

Comfort now, discomfort later. Discomfort now, not only comfort later, but resilience, adaptation, and growth as well. 

The same principle applies to workouts, skill building, meditation, nutrition, relationships, etc. Why wouldn't it apply in some way to sleep?
